0.body: mchdir is a command-line tool written in Rust that allows you to create a new directory and immediately change into it. It includes shell integration that defines an mcd command in your shell, simplifying directory creation and navigation.
0.title: Introduction

1.body: mchdir provides a convenient way to create a new directory and change into it in a single command. While similar functionality can be achieved with a shell script, this project serves as a demonstration of how to create a command-line tool in Rust with shell integration. Additionally, mchdir includes the mct command to create and enter directories in the system's temporary folder.
1.title: Description

10.body: If automatic installation does not work for your shell, you can manually add the integration code to your shell configuration file.
10.breadcrumbs: Shell Integration » Manually Add the Integration Code
10.title: Manually Add the Integration Code

11.body: Add the following code to your shell's configuration file: eval "$(mchdir init)"
11.breadcrumbs: Shell Integration » Bash, Zsh (and other Bash-Like Shells)
11.title: Bash, Zsh (and other Bash-Like Shells)

12.body: Add the following code to your ~/.config/fish/config.fish file: eval (mchdir init)
12.title: Fish Shell

13.body: After installing mchdir, use the following commands:
13.title: Usage

14.body: Create a new directory and change into it: mcd my_new_directory Change to the home directory (when no argument is provided): mcd Display help for the mcd command: mcd --help
14.title: mcd Command

15.body: Create a new directory in the system temporary directory and change into it: mct my_temp_directory Create a truly random directory in the system temporary directory: mct Display help for the mct command: mct --help
15.title: mct Command

16.body: The mchdir command supports the following subcommands: Display the shell integration code: mchdir init Install the shell integration automatically: mchdir install
16.title: mchdir Command

2.body: Create a new directory and change into it with a single command. Create a new directory in the system temporary directory and change into it with the mct command. Shell integration for bash, zsh, and fish shells. Supports automatic installation of shell integration scripts.
2.title: Features

3.body: To install mchdir, you can use crates.io, build it from source, or install it directly from GitHub.
3.title: Installation

4.body: Rust programming language (for building from source) cargo package manager Linux or macOS ( Windows is not supported )
4.title: Prerequisites

5.body: You can install the mchdir command from the crates.io registry using the following command: cargo install mchdir
5.title: Install from Crates.io

6.body:
Clone the repository: git clone https://github.com/seapagan/mchdir.git
cd mchdir Build the project: cargo build --release This will produce an executable in the target/release directory. Install the Executable: Copy the executable to a directory in your $PATH, for example: sudo cp target/release/mchdir /usr/local/bin/
6.title: Build from Source

7.body: You can also install the mchdir command directly from GitHub using the following command: cargo install --git https://github.com/seapagan/mchdir.git Once installed, you need to enable shell integration to use the mcd and mct commands. See the Shell Integration documentation (next) for more information.
7.title: Install from GitHub

8.body: To enable the mcd and mct commands in your shell, you need to integrate mchdir with your shell configuration.
8.title: Shell Integration

9.body: You can automatically install the shell integration by running: mchdir install This command will detect your shell and append the necessary integration code to the bottom of your shell configuration file (e.g., ~/.bashrc, ~/.zshrc, or ~/.config/fish/config.fish). If it detects that the integration code is already present, it will not add it again.
9.title: Automatic Installation
